      {
        "paragraph_index": 3,
        "text": "### Key Takeaways\n\n- **\"Amino Acids\" is the single largest named ligand class** in SRD-46, making up ~5.2% of all 5,750 ligands — reflecting the enormous importance of amino acids as metal chelators in biological and biochemical research.\n- There are **no similarly named classes** (e.g., \"Amino Acid Derivatives\") that could cause confusion — the class label \"Amino Acids\" is unique and unambiguous in the database.\n- The closely related **\"Peptides\"** (157), **\"polypeptides\"** (98), and **\"tripeptides\"** (66) classes are separate, so the 297 count is clean and does not include peptide ligands.\n\n> **Source:** NIST SRD-46 — Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes Database",
